<tr><td>Hays CISD</td><td>2010</td><td class="savings">Passed</td><td>Full-service ACC Hays Campus in Kyle/Buda corridor.</td></tr>
<tr><td>San Marcos CISD</td><td>2010</td><td>Failed</td><td>No campus. Continued out-of-district rates.</td></tr>
<tr><td>Bastrop ISD</td><td>2010</td><td>Failed</td><td>No campus. Continued out-of-district rates.</td></tr>
<tr><td>Pflugerville ISD</td><td>2018</td><td>Failed (53.45%)</td><td>Still paying $286/credit hour. No dedicated ACC presence.</td></tr>
</tbody>
</table>
<p>The pattern is consistent: communities that voted yes received campuses, expanded enrollment, and tuition relief. Communities that voted no received none of those things.</p>

<h2>The petition process</h2>
<p>Texas Education Code requires a petition signed by at least 5% of registered voters in the PfISD territory to trigger an annexation election. If the petition qualifies, the ACC Board of Trustees calls an election. Only registered voters within PfISD territory vote. If approved, residents immediately receive in-district benefits. ACC cannot advocate for or against annexation. The decision rests entirely with voters.</p>
